Classical Models of Volatility and Correlation¶

Variance and Volatility¶

Volatility is the annualized standard deviation of the returns on an investment. Pitfalls arises when scaling standard deviation into an annualized form. For instance, volatility is much greater when there is positive serial correlation between returns than it is when the returns are i.i.d. The standard deviation of 10-day log returns is not directly comparable with the standard deviation of daily log returns. For this reason we usually transform the standard deviation into annualized terms

$$E(r_{ht}) = hμ $$$$V(r_{ht}) = hσ^2 $$
In [4]:

Annual volatility = 0.5
Weekly std = 0.04992301766027062

The assumption that one-period returns are i.i.d. implies that volatility is constant. But it is not realistic to assume that returns are generated by an i.i.d. process. Many models do not make this assumption, including stochastic volatility option pricing models and GARCH statistical models of volatility. Nevertheless the annualization of standard deviation described above has become the market convention for quoting volatility. It is applied to every estimate or forecast of standard deviation, whether or not it is based on an i.i.d. assumption for returns.

$$E(r_{ht}) = hμ $$$$AR(1) Scale Factor = ( h + 2 \dfrac {θ}{(1 - θ)^2} [(h - 1)(1 - θ) - θ(1 - θ^{h-1})])^{1/2} $$
In [5]:
#example 2
monthly_std = 0.05
#(a) if returns are iid
vol_iid =  monthly_std * np.sqrt(12)
#(b) if returns are AR(1)
ar_coeff = 0.25
scale_factor = (12 + 2*(ar_coeff / (1 - ar_coeff)**2)*((12 - 1)*(1 - ar_coeff) - ar_coeff*(1 - pow(ar_coeff,12 - 1))))
vol_ar = monthly_std * np.sqrt(scale_factor)
print("vol_iid = " + str(vol_iid))
print("vol_ar = " + str(vol_ar))
print("the volatility is higher in case of AR(1) compared to the iid assumption")

vol_iid = 0.17320508075688773
vol_ar = 0.21858128444638747
the volatility is higher in case of AR(1) compared to the iid assumption

Covariance and Correlation¶

Pearson’s correlation is only appropriate when two returns have an elliptical joint distribution such as the bivariate normal distribution

COVARIANCE MATRIX $$ V = DCD $$ D = diagonal matrix of standard deviations - C = correlation matrix

PORTFOLIO VARIANCE $$ σ_{Port}^2 = w'Vw $$ w = wights vector

In the equally weighted model the covariance matrix forecast and hence also the associated forecasts of volatilities and correlations are assumed to be equal to their estimates. This is the only possibility in the context of an equally weighted model, which assumes returns are i.i.d. Since the volatility and correlation parameters are constant over time, there is nothing in the model to distinguish an estimate from a forecast. It is usual to take the horizon for the forecast to be determined by the frequency of the data used to estimate the volatilities and correlations.

Exponentially weighted moving averages¶

$$ EWMA(X_{t-1}, ...., X_{1} | λ ) = \frac{X_{t-1} + λX_{t-2} + λ^2X_{t-3} + ... + λ^{t-2}X_{1}}{1 + λ + λ^2 + ... + λ^{t -2}} $$

where λ is a smoothing constant (decay parameter) 0 < λ < 1

Here variance and convariances may calulcated in form of recursion VARIANCE : $$ \hat{σ}_{t}^2 = (1 - λ)r_{t-1}^2 + λ\hat{σ}_{t-1}^2 $$ $(1 - λ)r_{t-1}^2$= intensity in reaction $λ\hat{σ}_{t-1}^2$= persistence in volatility

COVARIANCE: $$ \hat{σ}_{12,t}^2 = (1 - λ)r_{1,t-1}r_{2,t-1} + λ\hat{σ}_{12,t-1}^2 $$

a high λ gives little reaction to actual market events but great persistence in volatility; a low λ gives highly reactive volatilities that quickly die away How do we choose λ? It can be chosen to minimize the root mean sqaure error between the EWMA estimated of variance and squared returns

Time series model and cointegration¶

cointegration models are constructed in two stages:

  • the first stage examines the association in a long term equilibrium between the prices of a set of financial assets
  • the second stage is a dynamic model of correlation, called an error correction model, that is based on linear regression analysis of returns


The presence of cointegration also implies that there is a statistical causality between the returns. The returns on one asset tend to lag the returns on the other, so that large price changes in one asset tend to be followed, at some time in the future, by large price changes in the other. This type of statistical causality is called Granger causality
Cointegration has emerged as a powerful technique for investigating long term dependence in multivariate time series, not just between two asset prices or interest rates. The main advantage of cointegration is that it provides a sound statistical methodology for modelling both the long term equilibrium and the short term dynamics.

Stationary processes¶

A descrete stochastic process is stationary if:

  • $ E(X_{t}) $ is a finite constant
  • $ V(X_{t}) $ is a finite constant
  • the joint distribution of $ (X_{t}, X_{s}) $ depends om t - s

In case of weakly stationarity $COV(X_{t}, X_{s}) $ depends only on $ \lvert t - s \rvert $

pth order autogression model $$ X_{t} = α + Q_{1}X_{t-1} + Q_{2}X_{t-2} + ... + Q_{p}X_{t-p} + ε_{t}, \quad ε_{t} \sim i.i.d(0, σ^2) $$ Moving Average Model MA(1) $$ X_{t} = ε_{t} + φε_{t-1}, \quad ε_{t} \sim i.i.d(0, σ^2) $$ ARMA(p,q) $$ X_{t} = α + Q_{1}X_{t-1} + Q_{2}X_{t-2} + ... + Q_{p}X_{t-p} + ε_{t} + φ_{1}ε_{t-1} + ... + φ_{q}ε_{t-q}, \quad ε_{t} \sim i.i.d(0, σ^2) $$

Stochastic trend¶

Random Walk: $$ X_{t} = X_{t-1} + ε_{t}, \quad ε_{t} \sim i.i.d(0, σ^2) $$ Random walk with drift: $$ X_{t} = α + X_{t-1} + ε_{t} $$

the random walk has infinite unconditional mean and variance. Since X t−1 is known and therefore not random at time t, the conditional mean and conditional variance, i.e. the mean and variance taken at every step in the random walk, are finite and are given by; $$ E_{t-1}(X_{t-1}) = α + X_{t-1} \quad and \quad V_{t-1}(X_{t}) = σ^2 $$

A time series process is said to be integrated of order i and denoted I(1) if it is not stationary but its first difference has a stationary ARMA representation. Hence, the random walk model is just one particular type of integrated process, one in which the first difference is i.i.d. More generally, the first difference of an integrated process can have autocorrelated and moving average components. It just needs to be stationary. $$ X_{t} \sim I(1) \Leftrightarrow X_{t} = α + X_{t-1} + ε_{t} \quad with \quad ε_{t} \sim I(0) $$

we use the notation I(0) as before to denote that a series is stationary.
When a process is integrated of order 1 we say that it has a stochastic trend. For instance, the random walk model has a stochastic trend as well as a drift determined by the sign and magnitude of the constant α.

UNIT ROOTS TEST:
Statistical tests of the null hypothesis that a time series is non-stationary versus the alternative that it is stationary are called unit root tests. The name derives from the fact that an autoregressive process is stationary if and only if the roots of its characteristic polynomial lie strictly inside the unit circle

from scipy import stats

# ensures experiment runs the same every time
np.random.seed(100)

# This function simluates an AR process, generating a new value based on historial values,
# autoregressive coefficients b1 ... bk, and some randomness.
def AR(b, X, mu, sigma):
    l = min(len(b)-1, len(X))
    b0 = b[0]
    
    return b0 + np.dot(b[1:l+1], X[-l:]) + np.random.normal(mu, sigma)

q1 = np.array([0, 0.9])
X1 = np.array([1])

q2 = np.array([0, 0.8])
X2 = np.array([1])

q3 = np.array([0, 0.7])
X3 = np.array([1])

mu = 0
sigma = 1

for i in range(100):
    X1 = np.append(X1, AR(q1, X1, mu, sigma))
    X2 = np.append(X2, AR(q2, X2, mu, sigma))
    X3 = np.append(X3, AR(q3, X3, mu, sigma))
    
plt.plot(X1)
plt.title('First oreder autocorrelation coeffcient q = 0.9')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('AR Series Value');
plt.show()

plt.plot(X2)
plt.title('First oreder autocorrelation coeffcient q = 0.8')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('AR Series Value');
plt.show()

plt.plot(X3)
plt.title('First oreder autocorrelation coeffcient q = 0.7')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('AR Series Value');
plt.show()

PCA¶

PCA may be applied to any covariance or correlation matrix based on returs or P&L.
Primary aims:

  • reduce the number of risk factors
  • identify the key source of risk
  • facilitate the measurament of portofolio risk

Review of Principal Components Analysis¶

Consider a set of n returns with time series data summarized in a T × n matrix X and let V be the covariance matrix (or correlation matrix) of X. The principal components of V are the columns of the T × n matrix P defined by $$ P = XW $$ where W is the n × n orthogonal matrix of eigenvectors of V. Since W is orthogonal, W−1 = W and so $$ X = PW' $$ A major aim of PCA is to use only a reduced set of principal components to represent the original variables X. For this purpose W is ordered so that the first column of W is the eigenvector corresponding to the largest eigenvalue of V, the second column of W is the eigenvector corresponding to the second eigenvalue of V, and so on. The mth principal component is the mth column of P, i.e. the column that is derived from the mth column of W. When we order the columns of W as above then the sum of squares of the elements in the mth principal component is the mth largest eigenvalue of V, denoted m. The total variation in X is the sum of the eigenvalues of V and the proportion of this total variation that is explained by the mth principal component is: $$ \frac{ λ_{M}}{ λ_{1} +...+ λ_{n}} $$ So between them the first k principal components of the returns capture a proportion $$ \frac{λ_{1} +...+ λ_{k}}{ λ_{1} +...+ λ_{n}} $$ Now we can choose k as follows. Either
• adjust k to capture a certain fixed proportion of the variation, such as 90% or 95%;
• set the number of principal components, such as k = 3 or k = 5, and then find how much of the variation is being captured by these components

Performing principal component analysis decomposes the matrix C into:

$$ C=LPL⊤ $$

where P is a diagonal matrix $ P=diag(λ1,λ2,…,λm) $, with $ λ1≥λ1≥…λm≥0 $ being the eigenvalues of matrix C . The matrix L is an orthogonal matrix, consisting the eigenvectors of matrix C .

ARCH and GARCH¶

The moving average models are based on the assumption that returns are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.). But we know that the i.i.d. assumption is very unrealistic. The volatility of financial asset returns changes over time, with periods when volatility is exceptionally high interspersed with periods when volatility is unusually low. This volatility clustering behaviour does, of course, depend on the frequency of the data.
The generalized autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity (GARCH) models of volatility that were introduced by Engle (1982) and Bollerslev (1986) are specifically designed to capture the volatility clustering of returns. The forecasts that are made from these models are not equal to the current estimate. Instead volatility can be higher or lower than average over the short term but as the forecast horizon increases the GARCH volatility forecasts converge to the long term volatility.
• the approach is autoregressive because GARCH is a time series model with an autoregressive (regression on itself) form;
• and we speak of conditional heteroscedasticity because time variation in conditional variance is built into the model. The unconditional variance is just the variance of the unconditional returns distribution, which is assumed constant over the entire data period considered. It can be thought of as the long term average variance over that period.
The conditional variance, on the other hand, will change at every point in time because it depends on the history of returns up to that point. That is, we account for the dynamic properties of returns by regarding their distribution at any point in time as being conditional on all the information up to that point. We denote the information set, which is the set containing all the past returns up to and including time t − 1, by It−1.

THE SYMMETRIC NORMAL GARCH MODEL¶

It assumes that the dynamic behaviour of the conditional variance is given by the following conditional variance equation: $$ σ_{t}^2 = w + αε_{t-1}^2 + Bσ_{t-1}^2 \quad ε_{t}, I_{t-1} \sim N(0 , σ_{t}^2) $$ The GARCH conditional volatility is defined as the annualized square root of this conditional variance. The conditional variance and volatility are conditional on the information set. Since the conditional variances at different points in time are related the process is not identically distributed and neither is it independent at different points in time are related.

LONG TERM VOLATILITY:
The long term or unconditional variance is: $$ \barσ_{t}^2 = \frac{w}{1 - (α + B)} $$

INTERPRETATION:
• The GARCH error parameter $\textbf α $ measures the reaction of conditional volatility to market shocks. When α is relatively large (e.g. above 0.1) then volatility is very sensitive to market events.
• The GARCH lag parameter $\textbf β $ measures the persistence in conditional volatility irrespective of anything happening in the market. When β is relatively large (e.g. above 0.9) then volatility takes a long time to die out following a crisis in the market.
• The sum $ \textbf α + β $ determines the rate of convergence of the conditional volatility to the long term average level. When α + β is relatively large (e.g. above 0.99) then the terms structure of volatility forecasts from the GARCH model is relatively flat.
• The GARCH constant parameter $ \textbf w $, together with the sum α + β, determines the level of the long term average volatility, i.e. the unconditional volatility in the GARCH model.

In [6]:
def simulate_GARCH(T, a0, a1, b1, sigma1):
    
    # Initialize our values
    X = np.ndarray(T)
    sigma = np.ndarray(T)
    sigma[0] = sigma1
    
    for t in range(1, T):
        # Draw the next x_t
        X[t - 1] = sigma[t - 1] * np.random.normal(0, 1)
        # Draw the next sigma_t
        sigma[t] = math.sqrt(a0 + b1 * sigma[t - 1]**2 + a1 * X[t - 1]**2)
        
    X[T - 1] = sigma[T - 1] * np.random.normal(0, 1)    
    
    return X, sigma

VALUE AT RISK¶

Value at risk (VaR) is a statistic used to try and quantify the level of financial risk within a firm or portfolio over a specified time frame. VaR provides an estimate of the maximum loss from a given position or portfolio over a period of time

We'll use historical VaR, which looks at previous returns distributions and uses that to compute the p percentile. This percentile is the amount of loss you could reasonably expect to experience with probability p , assuming future returns are close to past returns

Parametric¶

you assume that the returns follow a given distribution rather than non-parametrically estiamting it historically. We can check this by using a normal distribution Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF), which sums the area under a normal curve to figure out how likely certain values are. $$ VAR_{α} = u - σN^{-1}(α) $$

Montecarlo Simulation¶

The Monte Carlo simulation is a probability model which generates random variables used in tandem with economic factors (expected return, volatility — in the case of a portfolio of funds) to predict outcomes over a large spectrum.

In [68]:
